<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-605-064  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 605 064.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer-Aided Engineering  June 1990 v9 n6 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hardware rides in new saddle. (Houston Instrument)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Carrabine, Laura.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Houston Instrument is acquired by Summagraphics Corp for $30.2million.andP;  HI will become the Digitizer Division of Summagraphics.andO;New products from HI include the Scan-CAD 128 AMC, an opticalscanning tool to make an HI DMP-60 series pen plotter become anoptical scanner.andP;  The Scan-CAD, which costs $2,995, eliminatesmanually digitizing existing images and makes plotters becomehigh-resolution scanners.andP;  Three free software packages come withthe Scan-CAD 128 AMC.andP;  The LDS 4000 from HI is amicrocomputer-based scanner that digitizes documents up to E.DINA0 oversize; it costs $13,995.andP;  The LDS 4000 scans drawings into acomputer for conversion to computer-aided design, manipulation, orstorage.andP;  Software comes with the LDS 4000 to control scanningfunctions and for raster viewing, windowing, and printing.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ametek Inc. Houston Instrument Div. (product introduction)Summagraphics Corp. (acquisitions and mergers).andO;Product:   Houston Instrument Scan-CAD 128 AMC (Scanning device) (productintroduction)Houston Instrument LDS 4000 (Scanning device) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     AcquisitionScanningCAD-CAM.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>